‚úÖ What is a Forward Contract (FWC / FWCO) in Trade Finance?

A Forward Contract (FWC) is an agreement between a customer (exporter/importer) and the bank (like SBI) to buy or sell foreign currency at a fixed rate on a future date.

üëâ Why?

To protect the customer from foreign exchange rate fluctuations.

üëâ Used By:
	‚Ä¢	Exporters (who will receive foreign currency later)
	‚Ä¢	Importers (who need to pay foreign currency later)

üëâ In SBI Systems:
	‚Ä¢	FWCO = Forward Contract ‚Äì Outgoing / Forward Contract Booking
	‚Ä¢	FWCI = Forward Contract ‚Äì Incoming / Forward Utilization

Some banks use slightly different codes, but SBI‚Äôs trade finance system uses FWCO for booking.

‚∏ª

üéØ Example (SBI ‚Äì Forward Contract Booking)

Case: Importer example

ABC Importers (India) need to pay USD 100,000 to a supplier after 3 months.

Current USD/INR = ‚Çπ84.20

But they worry the rate may go to 86 or 87.

They go to SBI and book a forward contract:
	‚Ä¢	Type: FWCO
	‚Ä¢	Amount: USD 100,000
	‚Ä¢	Tenor: 3 months (value date)
	‚Ä¢	Rate fixed: ‚Çπ84.50 (Bank gives forward premium)

Now the importer is protected ‚Äî no matter market rate goes up, SBI must give USD at ‚Çπ84.50.

‚∏ª

üéØ Example (Exporters)

XYZ Exporter will receive USD 50,000 after 2 months.

Market rate today: ‚Çπ84.20
They worry USD may fall to 82 or 81 later.

They book FWCO with SBI:
	‚Ä¢	Amount: USD 50,000
	‚Ä¢	Tenor: 2 months
	‚Ä¢	Rate fixed: ‚Çπ84.30

Now exporter is protected from loss.

‚∏ª

üßæ How SBI Handles Forward Contracts Internally

In SBI Trade Finance (and similar bank software):

1Ô∏è‚É£ Booking (FWCO)
	‚Ä¢	Customer requests contract
	‚Ä¢	Bank checks limits (LC limit, FBP/FBD limit, FX exposure)
	‚Ä¢	Bank fixes forward rate
	‚Ä¢	Contract booked with a unique Forward Contract Number
	‚Ä¢	LIEN marked on the customer‚Äôs FX limit
	‚Ä¢	Accounting entries passed

2Ô∏è‚É£ Utilization (FWCI)

Whenever:
	‚Ä¢	Import bill comes for payment
	‚Ä¢	Export bill is purchased/realized

Bank uses (utilizes) part or full of the forward contract.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Cancellation

If customer doesn‚Äôt use the contract, SBI cancels it.

Cancellation requires:
	‚Ä¢	Rebooking rate difference
	‚Ä¢	Cancellation charge
	‚Ä¢	Swap cost depending on market

4Ô∏è‚É£ Extension / Rollover

If customer needs extension, SBI rebooks with new maturity date.

‚∏ª

üè¶ SBI Example ‚Äì How it looks in Bank System

‚úî Final Summary (Very Simple)

Forward Contract (FWCO) = Agreement with SBI to lock a fixed foreign exchange rate for future payment/receipt to avoid loss due to rate fluctuation.

‚∏ª

